<TITLE>Paul Carlucci writes beautifully about ugliness</TITLE>


<TEXT>
A Plea for Constant Motion , the second collection of short stories from Ottawa writer Paul Carlucci, opens with My New Best Friend in Exile. The story <EVENT eid="e1" class="I_STATE">seems</EVENT>, initially, to be one of connection, of a loner, Wes, a former high school art teacher <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">forced</EVENT> out of his job and <EVENT eid="e3" class="I_ACTION">trying</EVENT>, unsuccessfully, to <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">build</EVENT> a life in the city. Despite the ghosts of the <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="PAST_REF">past</TIMEX3> hanging over him, his neighbour Randy seems to be a steadying influence, perhaps even a friend. They <EVENT eid="e5" class="STATE">work</EVENT> together, <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">building</EVENT> a new porch for Wess house, and <EVENT eid="e7" class="I_STATE">drink</EVENT> together once construction is done, <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">lounging</EVENT> like gods after a long epic <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">act</EVENT> of creation. 
 
Wes <EVENT eid="e10" class="I_STATE">reflects</EVENT> on his neighbour: I <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">liked</EVENT> Randys thoughtful nature. I <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_ACTION">liked</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e13" class="I_ACTION">imagine</EVENT> him <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">shrunk</EVENT> down to adolescence, his brawny arms across the desks of one of my art classes, a bad kid in some peoples eyes, but not in mine. As the story twists to a close, though, it <EVENT eid="e15" class="I_STATE">becomes</EVENT> clear that Randy is, in fact, bad (this is a crushing understatement), a truth which Wes remains somehow unable to fully <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">see</EVENT>. 
 
Its a shocking and haunting story and in many ways My New Best Friend in Exile is characteristic of the <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">collection</EVENT> as a whole. These are stories of heartbreak and betrayal, of limited vision and wilful blindness, stories <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">laced</EVENT> with booze, drugs, sex, secrets and unemployment, with casual (and caustic) misogyny, racism, classism and violence. The stories are, as a rule, devoid of outer commentary or narrative <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">distancing</EVENT>, <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">forcing</EVENT> the reader to <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">confront</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">reconcile</EVENT> the often disturbing mindsets and occurrences which mark the work. 
 
It <EVENT eid="e23" class="STATE">doesnt</EVENT> make for easy reading, but A Plea for Constant Motion has an air of urgency to it, a sense of relevance which is at <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="X">once</TIMEX3> odd for a <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">collection</EVENT> of short stories and <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">disturbing</EVENT> in and of itself. 
 
Carlucci, whose first collection The Secret Life of Fission was <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">awarded</EVENT> the Danuta Gleed Award, writes beautifully of ugliness, <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">immersing</EVENT> the reader in the minds and hearts of characters most of us would like to <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">avoid</EVENT>, or, more critically, would <EVENT eid="e29" class="I_ACTION">prefer</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">believe</EVENT> didnt exist. Its a perfect collection for a world which confronts us with increasing violence and ugliness <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="SET" value="P1D">every day</TIMEX3>. 
